  "prompt": "What is the highest temperature ever recorded in the universe?",
  "response": "The highest temperature ever recorded in the universe is believed to have occurred during the Big Bang, where temperatures reached around \\(10^{32}\\) degrees Kelvin. In more controlled settings, such as particle accelerators, extremely high temperatures have been achieved. For example, the CERN Large Hadron Collider has created temperatures of about \\(5.5 \\times 10^{12}\\) degrees Kelvin (around 5.5 trillion degrees) during heavy ion collisions. These extreme conditions replicate the state of matter just moments after the Big Bang, allowing scientists to study fundamental particles and the early universe.",
